00:09:43.020 --> 00:09:46.370
As I said, to put HALS in
context, I really need to speak

00:09:46.370 --> 00:09:50.050
about the Historic
American Building Survey.

00:09:50.050 --> 00:09:54.040
Very briefly, it is a Roosevelt
administration initiative

00:09:54.040 --> 00:09:58.180
under the aegis of the WPA to
provide temporary employment

00:09:58.180 --> 00:09:59.990
for architects and
draftsmen unemployed

00:09:59.990 --> 00:10:01.290 position:56%
as a result of the Great Depression.

00:10:01.290 --> 00:10:05.630
Like I said, volumes have
been written about HABS,

00:10:05.630 --> 00:10:07.690
but for our purposes and
in the simplest terms,

00:10:07.690 --> 00:10:08.990
it is one of the anchors

00:10:08.990 --> 00:10:11.800
of our federal government's
preservation programs.

00:10:11.800 --> 00:10:13.670
Hundreds of architects, draftsmen

00:10:13.670 --> 00:10:17.910
and photographers were hired
temporarily for a four-month period

00:10:17.910 --> 00:10:22.500
across the United States to produce
measured architectural drawings,

00:10:22.500 --> 00:10:27.600
written history and large-format
photography of the complete resume

00:10:27.600 --> 00:10:31.670
of the American builders' art,
and thanks to significant input

00:10:31.670 --> 00:10:34.660
from the Library of Congress,
everything was completed

00:10:34.660 --> 00:10:38.050
in standardized formats,
was to be durable,

00:10:38.050 --> 00:10:40.820
reproducible and verifiable.

00:10:40.820 --> 00:10:42.120
Why do this?

00:10:42.120 --> 00:10:43.710
Well, the obvious reason
is of course

00:10:43.710 --> 00:10:47.410
to employ the struggling
architects of the period

00:10:47.410 --> 00:10:50.250
or at least provide them
some temporary relief,

00:10:50.250 --> 00:10:53.770 position:56%
but more importantly, the collateral
benefits of these documents turned

00:10:53.770 --> 00:10:56.930
out to be far more than
an academic record.

00:10:56.930 --> 00:10:59.540
In the burgeoning historic
preservation movement during the

00:10:59.540 --> 00:11:03.120
1920s -- '26 is Colonial
Williamsburg, et cetera --

00:11:03.120 --> 00:11:07.040
these drawings, history and
photographs proved to be invaluable

00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:10.260
to provide existing condition
documentation as the basis

00:11:10.260 --> 00:11:13.380
for restoration, insurance
needs for historic structures,

00:11:13.380 --> 00:11:15.650
interpretative needs
and fundamentally

00:11:15.650 --> 00:11:19.600
to maintain the resources
and the facility management.

00:11:19.600 --> 00:11:23.620
I'd love to show you a
couple early HABS examples.

00:11:23.620 --> 00:11:25.190
That one there, by
the way -- pardon me.

00:11:25.190 --> 00:11:28.200
On top is the General Cowles
House in Farmington, Connecticut,

00:11:28.200 --> 00:11:29.920
a wonderful neoclassical structure.

00:11:29.920 --> 00:11:32.350
On the right is the large format
photographic, on the left,

00:11:32.350 --> 00:11:35.900
the measured drawing, and
beneath it is the plan

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:39.250
of the ruin San Juan
Capistrano in California.

00:11:39.250 --> 00:11:42.800
One of my very favorite
drawings in the collection,

00:11:42.800 --> 00:11:47.910
this is the Le Pretre Mansion,
drawn in 1934, in New Orleans

00:11:47.910 --> 00:11:50.750
