00:18:00.030 --> 00:18:02.600
of information, and I
encourage you just to go

00:18:02.600 --> 00:18:05.470
to the Library's collection,
our collection at the Library.

00:18:05.470 --> 00:18:06.770
It is staggering.

00:18:06.770 --> 00:18:10.940 position:56%
I think it's currently just shy of
45,000 sites or something like that.

00:18:10.940 --> 00:18:14.190
It's been functioning
now 80-plus years.

00:18:14.190 --> 00:18:16.820
So now, let's have a little fun.

00:18:16.820 --> 00:18:22.680 position:56%
I was musing over some examples that
might have influenced my thinking

00:18:22.680 --> 00:18:27.350
in a less serious way, maybe
more of a popular culture way,

00:18:27.350 --> 00:18:30.470
to explore HALS's documentation
of historically

00:18:30.470 --> 00:18:35.210
and botanically significant trees,
linking together the historic

00:18:35.210 --> 00:18:38.310
and cultural side of the National
Park Service with the scientific

00:18:38.310 --> 00:18:40.540
and natural side of the
National Park Service.

00:18:40.540 --> 00:18:44.490
We tend not to play in the same
sandbox, and they have a lot more

00:18:44.490 --> 00:18:46.970
on the natural side, so we're
always struggling on this side.

00:18:46.970 --> 00:18:50.660
So I'm always trying to find
money, to raise money for projects,

00:18:50.660 --> 00:18:52.050
so this idea sort of coalesced.

00:18:52.050 --> 00:18:54.460
Maybe we can figure
some way to use trees

00:18:54.460 --> 00:18:56.930
to knit the two together a
little bit and have some fun

00:18:56.930 --> 00:18:58.410
and do some serious documentation,

00:18:58.410 --> 00:19:03.750
so I hope you'll recognize
this image.

00:19:03.750 --> 00:19:08.150
It is the famous talking apple tree

00:19:08.150 --> 00:19:13.110
in Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer's 1939
fantasy adventure The Wizard of Oz,

00:19:13.110 --> 00:19:16.240
the tree encountered by Dorothy,
Toto, the Tin Man, the Lion

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:17.900
and the Scarecrow on their way

00:19:17.900 --> 00:19:19.840
down the Yellow Brick
Road to Emerald City.

00:19:19.840 --> 00:19:23.430 position:56%
The Library of Congress has declared
this book America's greatest

00:19:23.430 --> 00:19:26.210 position:56%
and best-loved homegrown fairy tale.

00:19:26.210 --> 00:19:30.040
I like to refer to this
particular scene as the vegan slap,

00:19:30.040 --> 00:19:33.740
where the tree, in a very angry,
stentor voice says, "How would you

00:19:33.740 --> 00:19:37.370
like to have someone come along
and pick something off of you?"

00:19:37.370 --> 00:19:41.020
This particular apple tree
is not just a living thing,

00:19:41.020 --> 00:19:44.250
but it could actually breathe
and speak, it actually argues,

00:19:44.250 --> 00:19:46.770
and of course throws apples.

00:19:46.770 --> 00:19:50.650
Or how about the remarkable
Swiss Family Robinson treehouse?

00:19:50.650 --> 00:19:52.440
Every child's dream.

00:19:52.440 --> 00:19:55.180
The romance of a treehouse, in
this case a treehouse on steroids

00:19:55.180 --> 00:19:58.090
from the 1960 movie
of the same name.

00:19:58.090 --> 00:20:00.040
Would I have loved to
have had that treehouse.

00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:02.740 position:56%
But indeed, my fantasy was realized.

00:20:02.740 --> 00:20:04.880
A hundred and fifty-ton concrete

00:20:04.880 --> 00:20:09.700
and reinforced steel Swiss
Family treehouse opened in 1962

00:20:09.700 --> 00:20:15.060
in Adventureland at Disneyland,
and it only required a sea ticket.

00:20:15.060 --> 00:20:19.990
The whole thing, though, was
recreated in 1971 at Disney World,

00:20:19.990 --> 00:20:25.660 position:56%
recreated in 1992 at Euro Disneyland
and finally again in Tokyo Disney

00:20:25.660 --> 00:20:31.390
in 1993, a truly sort of
pan-cultural tree experience.

00:20:31.390 --> 00:20:32.690
Or how about this one?

00:20:32.690 --> 00:20:35.370
I don't know if you recognize
this one, the Whomping Willow.

00:20:35.370 --> 00:20:39.010
It debuted in Harry Potter
and the Goblet of Fire.

00:20:39.010 --> 00:20:42.150
It is a very violent
species of magical plant,

00:20:42.150 --> 00:20:44.020
sort of a tree with
a mean personality.

00:20:44.020 --> 00:20:47.280
Whomping Willows -- are there
any botanists in the audience?

00:20:47.280 --> 00:20:48.580
I don't know.

00:20:48.580 --> 00:20:49.880
I can't resist this.

00:20:49.880 --> 00:20:51.420
It's a Salix whompus.

00:20:51.420 --> 00:20:52.720
I couldn't resist.

00:20:52.720 --> 00:20:56.870
It will attack anything
and anyone that comes

00:20:56.870 --> 00:20:59.020
within range of its branches.

00:20:59.020 --> 00:21:00.490
"We must not be hasty.

00:21:00.490 --> 00:21:03.350
Things will go as they will,
and there is no need to hurry

00:21:03.350 --> 00:21:06.980
to meet them," quoth Treebeard
from The Lord of the Rings.

00:21:06.980 --> 00:21:10.880
Treebeard is the oldest of the
Ents still left in Middle Earth,

00:21:10.880 --> 00:21:15.120
an ancient treelike being who is
sort of a shepherd of all trees.

00:21:15.120 --> 00:21:17.540
He has a very tall and
stiff-limbed appearance,

00:21:17.540 --> 00:21:19.880
with bark-like skin and leafy hair.

00:21:19.880 --> 00:21:23.190
According to books, Ents are
much stronger than trolls

00:21:23.190 --> 00:21:25.510
as trolls are just
crude imitation of Ents.

00:21:25.510 --> 00:21:29.310
And last but certainly not
least -- I could go on --

00:21:29.310 --> 00:21:34.910
the Tree of Souls from Avatar, the
source of all energy and light.

00:21:34.910 --> 00:21:37.810
I'm not fluent in Na'vi, so I
will not dare attempt the correct

00:21:37.810 --> 00:21:41.880
pronunciation, but it is a giant
willow-like tree that is a point

00:21:41.880 --> 00:21:45.270
of extreme spiritual
significance to the Na'vi,

00:21:45.270 --> 00:21:48.010
moreso than any other
location on the planet Pandora

00:21:48.010 --> 00:21:50.080
for at least 3,000 years.

00:21:50.080 --> 00:21:53.960 position:56%
The destruction of the Tree of Souls
would prove devastating to the Na'vi

00:21:53.960 --> 00:21:57.660
as a whole and would create
a cultural and religious void

00:21:57.660 --> 00:22:00.730
that would decimate
their race entirely.

00:22:02.010 --> 00:22:06.100
Such is the significance of trees
in our extremely creative fiction.

00:22:06.100 --> 00:22:07.830
My mind really did
wander in that one.

00:22:07.830 --> 00:22:10.430
I went to Paul Bunyan,
Johnny Appleseed.

00:22:10.430 --> 00:22:13.030
There are a lot of opportunities
to sort of relate trees

00:22:13.030 --> 00:22:16.940
in a popular way, but here are a
few quick examples of actual trees

00:22:16.940 --> 00:22:22.090
that elicit and evoke similar
responses, very profound responses.

00:22:22.090 --> 00:22:25.060
The redwoods at Muir
National Forest.

00:22:25.060 --> 00:22:28.440
The sequoia of California and
Oregon are among the largest

00:22:28.440 --> 00:22:32.080
and tallest trees in the world,
living for thousands of years.

00:22:32.080 --> 00:22:36.560
John Steinbeck wrote about
redwood in 1961 in his Travels

00:22:36.560 --> 00:22:38.770
with Charley in Search of America.

00:22:38.770 --> 00:22:42.890
"The redwoods, once seen,
leave a mark or create a vision

00:22:42.890 --> 00:22:45.080
that stays with you always.

00:22:45.080 --> 00:22:46.870
No one has every successfully
painted

00:22:46.870 --> 00:22:49.280
or photographed a redwood tree.

00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:52.180
The feeling they produce
is not transferable.

00:22:52.180 --> 00:22:54.310
From them comes silence and awe,

00:22:54.310 --> 00:22:59.470 position:56%
and it's not only their unbelievable
stature nor the color which seems

00:22:59.470 --> 00:23:01.600
to shift and vary under our eyes.

00:23:01.600 --> 00:23:04.350
No, they're not like
any other trees we know.

00:23:04.350 --> 00:23:07.020
They are ambassadors
from another time."

00:23:07.020 --> 00:23:09.920
Or how about the Avenue
of Oaks from Oak Alley?

00:23:09.920 --> 00:23:11.490
The grand dame of the
great river road,

00:23:11.490 --> 00:23:15.080
Oak Alley Plantation is a
national historic landmark located

00:23:15.080 --> 00:23:17.630
on the west bank of the
Mississippi River in Vacherie,

00:23:17.630 --> 00:23:20.180 position:56%
the Saint James Parish in Louisiana.

00:23:20.180 --> 00:23:23.500
Oak Alley is named, of course, for
that distinguished visual feature,

00:23:23.500 --> 00:23:27.730
an alley created by a double
row of living southern live oaks

00:23:27.730 --> 00:23:31.700
about 800 feet long and planted
in the early 18th century,

00:23:31.700 --> 00:23:34.640
long before the present
Greek revival focal point

00:23:34.640 --> 00:23:36.320
in the picture was built.

00:23:36.320 --> 00:23:39.670
The alley or tree avenue runs
between the home and the river.

00:23:39.670 --> 00:23:43.330
And finally, of course, to sort
of bring it home a little bit,

00:23:43.330 --> 00:23:46.230
our White House Christmas tree,
the official indoor Christmas tree

00:23:46.230 --> 00:23:48.370
of the residence of the
president of the United States.

00:23:48.370 --> 00:23:52.240
Trust me, I came up with a lot
more popular culture examples,

00:23:52.240 --> 00:23:55.900
but hopefully these will be
sufficient to drive home the point

00:23:55.900 --> 00:23:58.830
of the role of influences
of trees in our society.

00:23:58.830 --> 00:24:01.500
Probably it'll be a
little blurry out there.

00:24:01.500 --> 00:24:04.580
Like I said, I was musing over a
way to connect the natural side

00:24:04.580 --> 00:24:06.810
with the culture side of
the National Park Service,

00:24:06.810 --> 00:24:08.430
and the idea of using trees

00:24:08.430 --> 00:24:12.070
that have witnessed significant
cultural events coalesced

00:24:12.070 --> 00:24:15.170
into the Witness Tree
Protection Program.

00:24:15.170 --> 00:24:17.800
I hope you see a little
humor in that one,

00:24:17.800 --> 00:24:19.850
but more seriously,
trees are landmarks.

00:24:19.850 --> 00:24:25.180
They are memorials, they identify
us, they identify human happenings,

00:24:25.180 --> 00:24:29.410
we love them and they carry their
associations through generations.

00:24:29.410 --> 00:24:31.080
The idea of somehow preserving them

00:24:31.080 --> 00:24:34.290
through documentation became
the core of the project.

00:24:34.290 --> 00:24:37.990
The national capital region of the
National Park Service embraced it

00:24:37.990 --> 00:24:41.310
and funded the project completely,
and we are off and running

00:24:41.310 --> 00:24:46.340
and completed HALS's
documentation on 24 witness trees

00:24:46.340 --> 00:24:51.350
as a pilot project for the nation,
and we'd like to show not all 24

00:24:51.350 --> 00:24:53.600
but a few of them briefly and
sort of soak you in the idea

00:24:53.600 --> 00:24:55.410
of what a witness tree is.

00:24:55.410 --> 00:24:59.760
The Burnside Bridge American
Sycamore, Platanus occidentalis,

00:24:59.760 --> 00:25:02.810
located at the Antietam
National Battlefield.

00:25:02.810 --> 00:25:06.050
The Burnside Bridge American
Sycamore is a living monument

00:25:06.050 --> 00:25:10.730
to those who fought there
on September 17th, 1862.

00:25:10.730 --> 00:25:13.420
With over 23,000 total casualties,

00:25:13.420 --> 00:25:16.680
the Battle of Antietam was not only
the bloodiest day of the Civil War

00:25:16.680 --> 00:25:19.810
but also the bloodiest day
in all of American history,

00:25:19.810 --> 00:25:24.090
and there you see a picture of
Union Army general Ambrose Everett

00:25:24.090 --> 00:25:26.400
Burnside, with those
great mutton chops.

00:25:26.400 --> 00:25:30.540
This tiny bridge played
a key role in the battle.

00:25:30.540 --> 00:25:33.890
Burnside and the Federal
9th Corp had been charged

00:25:33.890 --> 00:25:37.700
with first taking a stone
bridge spanning Antietam Creek.

00:25:37.700 --> 00:25:40.980
Burnside's attack was delayed some
five hours behind the original

00:25:40.980 --> 00:25:43.610
schedule, and when he
finally did attack,

00:25:43.610 --> 00:25:46.220
the entrenched Confederates
repelled several charges

00:25:46.220 --> 00:25:49.200
by concentrating their fire
on that narrow bridge opening

00:25:49.200 --> 00:25:52.010
on the creek's eastern bank.

00:25:52.010 --> 00:25:54.910
Burnside's force of
12,000 was held at bay

00:25:54.910 --> 00:25:58.260
by a mere 400 resolute Georgians,

00:25:58.260 --> 00:26:01.740
the brigade that held off
a corp. Standing beside

00:26:01.740 --> 00:26:04.390
that bridge is another
historic feature known

00:26:04.390 --> 00:26:07.040
as the Burnside Sycamore,
a witness tree.

00:26:07.040 --> 00:26:11.170
The tree can be seen in photos by
the famous Civil War photographer,

00:26:11.170 --> 00:26:15.450
in the lower right there, Alexander
Gardner, and over 150 years later,

00:26:15.450 --> 00:26:19.960
it still remains as a direct link
to the story and to the past.

00:26:19.960 --> 00:26:22.860
Or how about the Jackson
Magnolia, a magnolia grandiflora,

00:26:22.860 --> 00:26:25.310
located on the south
side of the White House?

00:26:25.310 --> 00:26:28.640
The Jackson Magnolia is a wonderful
hundred and eighty year-old story

00:26:28.640 --> 00:26:31.050
of a tree that replaced itself.

00:26:31.050 --> 00:26:33.170
This story started in 1829

00:26:33.170 --> 00:26:36.460
when President Andrew Jackson left
his Tennessee home and journeyed

00:26:36.460 --> 00:26:39.760
to the White House for his
inauguration and presidency.

00:26:39.760 --> 00:26:42.070
Legend has it he had
a sprout from one

00:26:42.070 --> 00:26:45.430
of his wife Rachel's
favorite magnolia trees.

00:26:45.430 --> 00:26:48.550
At that time, though, he was
in mourning for his wife,

00:26:48.550 --> 00:26:51.860
who had died just a few months
before his inauguration.

00:26:51.860 --> 00:26:54.990
Taking a sprout of the magnolia
tree obviously had a strong meaning

00:26:54.990 --> 00:26:58.560 position:56%
for Andrew Jackson, and the majestic
tree has had a strong meaning

00:26:58.560 --> 00:27:01.260
for many presidents since then
as well as their families.

00:27:01.260 --> 00:27:02.710
Franklin Delano Roosevelt

00:27:02.710 --> 00:27:04.750
and Winston Churchill
commented many times,

00:27:04.750 --> 00:27:08.430
"We sat underneath that
old magnolia tree."

00:27:08.430 --> 00:27:11.380
It's a remarkably durable
specimen and quite a survivor.

00:27:11.380 --> 00:27:15.780
You may recall in 1994 it was
hit by a two-seat Cessna plane.

00:27:15.780 --> 00:27:17.480
Hitting the south side of
the house, it hit the tree,

00:27:17.480 --> 00:27:19.890
did some serious damage,
but it's still there.

00:27:19.890 --> 00:27:21.890
And finally, to complete the story,

00:27:21.890 --> 00:27:27.000
a cutting from the Jackson Magnolia
made a return trip to the Hermitage

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:31.710
to replace the original tree that
was destroyed by a tornado in 1998.

00:27:31.710 --> 00:27:33.390
The War of 1812 Oak.

00:27:33.390 --> 00:27:34.690
It's a majestic tree.

00:27:34.690 --> 00:27:37.070
You can see the scale of it
next to those picked benches.

00:27:37.070 --> 00:27:41.430
A Quercus phellos located at Oxon
Hill Farm in Oxon Hill, Maryland,

00:27:41.430 --> 00:27:45.600
planted at least in the early 19th
century, possibly the 18th century.

00:27:45.600 --> 00:27:47.770
The tree has stood
as a living witness

00:27:47.770 --> 00:27:51.130
to a remarkable history
from the War of 1812.

00:27:51.130 --> 00:27:54.660
This is a 17th-century tract of
land overlooking the Potomac River

00:27:54.660 --> 00:27:56.660
and the future Washington, DC.

00:27:56.660 --> 00:28:00.740
Ultimately it became known as Oxon
Hill Manor and its house is known

00:28:00.740 --> 00:28:04.550
as Mount Welby, and that's
the view in the lower right

00:28:04.550 --> 00:28:07.720
from Mount Welby toward
DC as it was burning.

00:28:07.720 --> 00:28:11.410 position:56%
The estate was situated near some of
the worst fighting of the entire war

00:28:11.410 --> 00:28:15.700
and was in earshot of the Battle of
Bladensburg, and it was illuminated

00:28:15.700 --> 00:28:17.370
by the fires in our capital,

00:28:17.370 --> 00:28:22.080
and that remarkable willow
oak survives as a witness.

00:28:22.080 --> 00:28:26.710
One of my favorites, the Fort
Hunt Park Royal Visit Pin Oak,

00:28:26.710 --> 00:28:30.690
a Quercus palustris, down on the
George Washington Memorial Parkway

00:28:30.690 --> 00:28:32.840
at Fort Hunt Park.

00:28:32.840 --> 00:28:36.000
The Fort Hunt Park Royal
Visit Pin Oak is significant

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:38.220
because of its association
with the visitation

00:28:38.220 --> 00:28:43.750 position:56%
of England's King George the Sixth
and Queen Elizabeth in June of 1939.

00:28:43.750 --> 00:28:47.760
The tree commemorates the visit
to the Civilian Conservation Corp,

00:28:47.760 --> 00:28:51.600
the CCC, facility established
at Fort Hunt.

00:28:51.600 --> 00:28:54.570
President Roosevelt and First
Lady Eleanor Roosevelt used

00:28:54.570 --> 00:28:59.450
to showcase Fort Hunt as a model
facility for CCC and it played host

00:28:59.450 --> 00:29:03.580
to a great array of eminent
foreign leaders, including future,

00:29:03.580 --> 00:29:06.300
most prominent, the royal couple.

00:29:06.300 --> 00:29:09.760
Two pin oak trees were planted
in honor of the occasion.

00:29:09.760 --> 00:29:12.440
One of those trees still
survives today to witness.

00:29:12.440 --> 00:29:16.670
The Lady Bird Johnson Park
Crabapple, a Malus species,

00:29:16.670 --> 00:29:19.270
along the George Washington
Memorial Parkway.

00:29:19.270 --> 00:29:24.560
Lady Bird Johnson Park is actually
a manmade 157-acre island located

00:29:24.560 --> 00:29:27.880
immediately south of Theodore
Roosevelt Island along the Virginia

00:29:27.880 --> 00:29:31.110
shore of the Potomac
River at the west terminus

00:29:31.110 --> 00:29:32.910
of Arlington Memorial
Bridge and sort

00:29:32.910 --> 00:29:35.630
of the symbolic entrance
to the nation's capital.

00:29:35.630 --> 00:29:39.200
In 1901, the McMillan
Commission began to develop plans

00:29:39.200 --> 00:29:40.500
for the present design

00:29:40.500 --> 00:29:42.930
of Washington's city
beautiful, monumental core.

00:29:42.930 --> 00:29:44.970
Less well known, though,

00:29:44.970 --> 00:29:48.180
is the commission's plan
for a Columbia Island.

00:29:48.180 --> 00:29:51.090
In 1932, the Arlington
Memorial Bridge

00:29:51.090 --> 00:29:54.670
and the Mount Vernon Memorial
Parkway opened to the public.

00:29:54.670 --> 00:29:56.130
The last phase of the work

00:29:56.130 --> 00:30:00.300 position:56%
on the Mount Vernon Memorial Parkway
project included seeding the grass

00:30:00.300 --> 00:30:04.150
on Columbia Island and planting
approximately 75 ornamental

00:30:04.150 --> 00:30:05.860
flowering trees.

00:30:05.860 --> 00:30:08.260
A very few amount of
these crabapples exist

00:30:08.260 --> 00:30:12.150 position:56%
and this one certainly is a
mammoth example of a crabapple tree.

00:30:12.150 --> 00:30:16.810
I think my favorite, the Frederick
Douglass White Oak, Quercus alba,

00:30:16.810 --> 00:30:19.480
located at the Frederick
Douglass National Historic Site

00:30:19.480 --> 00:30:21.170
in southeast Washington, DC.

00:30:21.170 --> 00:30:23.020
Frederick Douglass, of course,

00:30:23.020 --> 00:30:27.270
was one of our nation's leading
abolitionists, author, editor,

00:30:27.270 --> 00:30:30.300
orator, reformer, statesman
and diplomat.

00:30:30.300 --> 00:30:31.990
He lived at Cedar Hill.

00:30:31.990 --> 00:30:34.870
He died there in 1895.

00:30:34.870 --> 00:30:38.010
The Frederick Douglass White Oak
commanded a prominent location

00:30:38.010 --> 00:30:39.310
in front of the property.

00:30:39.310 --> 00:30:41.360
You can see it in the
historic photograph.

00:30:41.360 --> 00:30:45.020
That same V in the branches exists
in the V in the large photograph

00:30:45.020 --> 00:30:47.610
on the other side of the image.

00:30:47.610 --> 00:30:49.840
It's located directly
outside his library

00:30:49.840 --> 00:30:52.160
and witnessed his hours
of long work.

00:30:52.160 --> 00:30:54.600
It was the largest remaining
tree in the property.

00:30:54.600 --> 00:30:57.990
Sadly it has died and
has been removed,

00:30:57.990 --> 00:31:00.450
the only remaining
archival record, of course,

00:31:00.450 --> 00:31:02.450
being the witness tree
documentation.

00:31:02.450 --> 00:31:06.940
The big daddy, Methuselah, the
willow oak, a Quercus phellos,

00:31:06.940 --> 00:31:10.130
located on the George Washington
Memorial Parkway right near one

00:31:10.130 --> 00:31:11.720
of the parking lots
near Belle Haven.

00:31:11.720 --> 00:31:15.270
If you ever driven north on the
George Washington Memorial Parkway

00:31:15.270 --> 00:31:16.570
from Mount Vernon, you more

00:31:16.570 --> 00:31:19.790
than likely have enjoyed those
incredibly beautiful banked curves,

00:31:19.790 --> 00:31:22.260
the landscaping, the views and sort

00:31:22.260 --> 00:31:25.140
of the way the parkway
integrates into the terrain.

00:31:25.140 --> 00:31:28.670
The George Washington Memorial
Parkway is actually the first

00:31:28.670 --> 00:31:31.550
comprehensively designed
modern roadway built

00:31:31.550 --> 00:31:32.850
by the federal government.

00:31:32.850 --> 00:31:35.810
There's several things that
you noticed when driving

00:31:35.810 --> 00:31:38.510
on it made it quite
revolutionary for its time.

00:31:38.510 --> 00:31:42.420
You may have also noticed one
such curve, those gracious curves,

00:31:42.420 --> 00:31:44.190
is gently interrupted
by sort of a hiccup

00:31:44.190 --> 00:31:46.910
for no immediately obvious reason,

00:31:46.910 --> 00:31:51.280
but if you go the desired
35 miles per hour,

00:31:51.280 --> 00:31:55.750
you may have noticed an immense
tree located relatively close

00:31:55.750 --> 00:31:57.050
to the road.

00:31:57.050 --> 00:31:59.370
The National Park Service
staff affectionately referred

00:31:59.370 --> 00:32:03.970
to this specimen, an immense
willow oak, as Methuselah.

00:32:03.970 --> 00:32:08.310 position:56%
Such respect commanded actually
altering the road alignment in order

00:32:08.310 --> 00:32:10.810
to preserve the massive tree.

00:32:10.810 --> 00:32:14.470
These mature trees, a Quercus
phellos, normally range in size

00:32:14.470 --> 00:32:18.860
from 40 to 60 feet tall with a
30 to 40-inch spread on the crown

00:32:18.860 --> 00:32:22.500
from about 110 to 220
inches around the trunk.

00:32:22.500 --> 00:32:25.600 position:56%
