00:32:45.060 --> 00:32:46.700
Just a few more.

00:32:46.700 --> 00:32:51.260 position:56%
In Georgetown, the Tudor Place Tulip
Poplar, a Liriodendron tulipifera,

00:32:51.260 --> 00:32:55.260
located in Georgetown, District
of Columbia on the great estate.

00:32:55.260 --> 00:32:58.800
The tulip poplar is one of the
largest and most valuable hardwoods

00:32:58.800 --> 00:33:00.340
of eastern North America.

00:33:00.340 --> 00:33:02.150
Its spread is unbelievable.

00:33:02.150 --> 00:33:05.550
It's from Connecticut and southern
New York to southern Ontario

00:33:05.550 --> 00:33:08.310
and northern Ohio all the way
down to Louisiana and Florida.

00:33:08.310 --> 00:33:10.250
It has a massive growth area.

00:33:10.250 --> 00:33:15.180
This particular Tudor Place tulip
poplar is significant due its

00:33:15.180 --> 00:33:18.700
association with the Peter family
of Georgetown and their development

00:33:18.700 --> 00:33:20.410
of the Tudor Place Estate.

00:33:20.410 --> 00:33:23.830
Tudor Place was designed by Doctor
William Thornton, same architect

00:33:23.830 --> 00:33:26.940
that designed the large structure
across the street, the US Capital,

00:33:26.940 --> 00:33:29.380
but this tree is an
absolutely massive specimen.

00:33:29.380 --> 00:33:33.630
It occupies an extremely prominent
location on the south lawn.

00:33:33.630 --> 00:33:37.700
Certainly among one of the oldest
tulip poplars in Washington, DC,

00:33:37.700 --> 00:33:41.640
growing since the beginning of
property's long 200-year evolution,

00:33:41.640 --> 00:33:46.610
and interestingly, Tudor Place is
the only private property protected

00:33:46.610 --> 00:33:48.900 position:56%
by a National Park Service easement.

00:33:48.900 --> 00:33:50.650
Here's a local boy or girl.

00:33:50.650 --> 00:33:56.770
This is the Union Square
Zelkova, a Zelkova carpinifolia,

00:33:56.770 --> 00:34:00.830
located just at the bottom of
the hill here and Union Square.

00:34:00.830 --> 00:34:05.060
The Botanic Garden elm is an
absolutely incredible ornamental

00:34:05.060 --> 00:34:07.970
shade tree unlike another
any other tree on the mall.

00:34:07.970 --> 00:34:10.800
It's significant because of
its rarity, its longevity

00:34:10.800 --> 00:34:13.700
and its association with
the original United States

00:34:13.700 --> 00:34:15.190
Botanic Garden.

00:34:15.190 --> 00:34:17.860
It is also significant
due to its preservation

00:34:17.860 --> 00:34:21.440
by Frederick Law Olmsted,
Junior, recognizing its uniqueness

00:34:21.440 --> 00:34:24.840
in the world and certainly in
Washington, DC during his redesign

00:34:24.840 --> 00:34:26.210
of the modern National Mall.

00:34:26.210 --> 00:34:30.890
In 1820, Congress authorized
the Columbian Institute

00:34:30.890 --> 00:34:33.280
for the Promotion of
Arts and Sciences

00:34:33.280 --> 00:34:36.380
to found first the United
States Botanic Garden

00:34:36.380 --> 00:34:39.250
on the site currently occupied
by Union Square at the base

00:34:39.250 --> 00:34:43.000
of the hill, by the water,
by the big lake down there,

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:45.280
an area approximately ten acres.

00:34:45.280 --> 00:34:48.990
In the 1850s, the first greenhouses
in the gardens were established.

00:34:48.990 --> 00:34:52.190
This historic photograph
shows the conservatory.

00:34:52.190 --> 00:34:55.560
It's about 300 feet long totally,

00:34:55.560 --> 00:34:58.070
with a central dome
and two long wings.

00:34:58.070 --> 00:34:59.840
The late 19th-century photograph

00:34:59.840 --> 00:35:02.840
