00:35:25.850 --> 00:35:30.490
And finally, the 1910 Japanese
flowering cherry trees,

00:35:30.490 --> 00:35:34.180
Prunus yedoensis, located
unusually, in this situation,

00:35:34.180 --> 00:35:39.670
on the East Potomac Golf Course,
East Potomac Park, Haynes Point.

00:35:39.670 --> 00:35:42.730 position:56%
You may all know that the history
of the famous flowering cherry trees

00:35:42.730 --> 00:35:45.830
of Washington, DC begins in 1885.

00:35:45.830 --> 00:35:50.240
A prominent city resident, a
travel writer and a photographer,

00:35:50.240 --> 00:35:54.230
Eliza Ruhamah Scidmore
first traveled to Japan.

00:35:54.230 --> 00:35:57.800
She was deeply impressed by the
beauty of the cherry blossoms

00:35:57.800 --> 00:36:00.450
and the prominent place that
this flowering tree holds

00:36:00.450 --> 00:36:02.510
in Japanese culture.

00:36:02.510 --> 00:36:08.120
Upon her return to Washington, DC,
she lobbied Congress for 24 years

00:36:08.120 --> 00:36:13.360
to plant those trees and
finally, in 1909, she decided --

00:36:13.360 --> 00:36:14.660
she was almost ready to give up.

00:36:14.660 --> 00:36:17.590
She decided to raise the money
herself and purchase the trees

00:36:17.590 --> 00:36:20.280
and then donate them to the city.

00:36:20.280 --> 00:36:23.970
She sent a letter explaining
all of this to First Lady Taft,

00:36:23.970 --> 00:36:25.730
who embraced the project
immediately,

00:36:25.730 --> 00:36:30.340
and this ultimately resulted
in a gift of 2,000 trees

00:36:30.340 --> 00:36:33.370
on behalf of the city of Tokyo.

00:36:33.370 --> 00:36:35.640
They arrived 1910.

00:36:35.640 --> 00:36:39.190
To the great disappointment of all
parties, a United States Department

00:36:39.190 --> 00:36:41.830
of Agricultural Inspection
team discovered

00:36:41.830 --> 00:36:46.870
that the trees had some insect
infection, so the USDA determined

00:36:46.870 --> 00:36:51.510
that the trees must be destroyed
and on the 20th of January,

00:36:51.510 --> 00:36:54.380
President William Howard Taft
reluctantly gave the order

00:36:54.380 --> 00:36:57.570
to burn the trees that his
wife had just helped acquire.

00:36:57.570 --> 00:37:01.500
A second and even more generous
donation of an even larger group

00:37:01.500 --> 00:37:06.630
of trees arrived in March of 1912,
with the first two trees planted

00:37:06.630 --> 00:37:10.280
by First Lady Taft and Viscountess
Chinda the following day.

00:37:10.280 --> 00:37:13.920
Those are the trees we know, and
now for the rest of the story.

00:37:13.920 --> 00:37:16.930
It has long been assumed
that none of the cherry trees

00:37:16.930 --> 00:37:20.540
from the 1910 shipment
survived destruction.

00:37:20.540 --> 00:37:22.110
That's simply not true.

00:37:22.110 --> 00:37:27.270
As we heard earlier, one of them
is here on the Library grounds

00:37:27.270 --> 00:37:32.060
on the southeast corner, I think
it is, and the rest of them,

00:37:32.060 --> 00:37:35.870
under recently discovered evidence
suggests that a small group of 24

00:37:35.870 --> 00:37:38.510
of them were taken
under close observation

00:37:38.510 --> 00:37:42.030
by government entomologists
for scientific analysis,

00:37:42.030 --> 00:37:45.360
and today approximately
18 of the 24 survive.

00:37:45.360 --> 00:37:48.980
They are very, very old
Yoshino cherry trees.

00:37:48.980 --> 00:37:52.440 position:56%
They're located on land now occupied
by the East Potomac Golf Course.

00:37:52.440 --> 00:37:56.310
They are not only the oldest but
some of the largest cherry trees

00:37:56.310 --> 00:37:59.320
in Washington, DC, but
they also survived more

00:37:59.320 --> 00:38:03.920
than twice their expected maximum
age that's expected for the species

00:38:03.920 --> 00:38:06.620
and they really have grown to an
extraordinary size, as you can see

00:38:06.620 --> 00:38:09.450
by some of the photographs.

00:38:09.450 --> 00:38:12.510
These witness trees are a living --

00:38:12.510 --> 00:38:18.910
these 1910 cherry trees and the
1912 cherry trees are a living

00:38:18.910 --> 00:38:22.640
and an enduring reminder of the
goodwill and friendship shared

00:38:22.640 --> 00:38:26.290
by the people of Japan
and the United States.

